<IFRAME FRAMEBORDER=1 ALIGN=CENTER width=100% HEIGHT=200 SCROLLING=YES SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/Forum1/HTML/000248.html">
<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#323232"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">If you wouldn't mind, I'd like to hear all your thoughts on backstabbing. This is a skill in survivor/path of thief which you need to learn in order to use the backstab ability of some weapons. The better you get, the higher your chance of backstabbing. Currently backstabbing gives you a free attack, but nothing is set in stone on that yet.<P>Lar</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Anthea</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">An additional attack, yes. Probably the enemy should not have a chance to parry the backstab-attack, or at least a vastly reduced chance. (And if he manages to parry it <B>very</B> good he might get an unparryable attack on you)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">In tabletop RPG sessions, I played a lot of fighter types. I disliked A LOT that at high level a thief with backstabbing skill could do more damage than I as a fighter could. And this was in regular fights.<P>Thus, yes: backstabbing is leathal in many cases and would offer you a enormous damage bonus, but backstabbing is useless in a normal fight, even if there are many places to hide (a battle fought in a forest e.g.) or even if the thief/backstabber can make himself invisible. Even then, he has to succeed in getting behind the victim, jump to him while the victim is fighting (moving a lot, wielding a weapon), then successfully grab him AND slit his throat.<P>Additionally: cutting the throat of somebody who is sleeping is not difficult for anybody. You do not need a lot of training for that.<P>So I am not really positive about the backstabbing skill, although I guess that's rather personal.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hilmar Haudrauf</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Backstabbing is skill that was originally introduced for balancing reasons, I guess.<BR>The fixed "thief" class would have been too weak in fights without it, so no one would have liked to play such a feeble character...<BR>With divinity (forgot how to get the nice image), this skill is superfluous and irritating, because strictly speaking, there are no "fixed classes".<BR>On the other hand, you might need it in the end due to balancing reasons...</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">major fatal</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">From a trusted source,<P>Well dante for the most part i agree with you, <BR>still do not overestimate the swiftness of a well trained assasin, he will never jump at you and grab you, hold you, for this actions will all take much to long!<BR>, rather he will make sure you slit your throat open on his knive!<BR>, or walk eyeblank on the point of his nife<P><BR>(a fact; a particular chinese military faction where learned to easily take out heavily armored and weaponed opponents in a single jaw! This was when they where gunpointed in the back and stilll they succeeded unhurted (the practice whas with sharp bullets and kevlar), so they did not even had to sneak. And we are talking about modern days here.)<P>Still such a thing should not be done easily, since it requires years and years of training to achieve this level of expertise!<BR>And thus be penaltied untill you reach a high level.<BR>Again dante i do agree, but it is possible to be THAT lethal in assasination.<P>THe somehow temporily shadowed paladine,<BR>meaning im undercover when i wrote this +:-)<BR>i cannot afford any more penance added to my retraitre!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Goemoe</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I think a free attack is ok. So the damage depends on the thiefs fighting ability and not on some weird rules which order unknown lots of damage for backstabbing.<P>This free attack is easy to comprehend for every one and easy to use.<P>Stay to the free attack.<P>I think this backstabbing as a bonus to keep a thief competitive has been a fault. Now all thiefs in all pnp system tend to have something like this. A thief has much more vital skills, than fighting. I know lots of adventures, where a thief or two were busy all the time and the wizards and warriors just stood there waiting for something to hit.<P>It is just a different class. One should not measure a class merely by its fighting ability.<P> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/cool.gif">Goemoe</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cybu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Actually,<P>if I'm not mistaking I know some (text based) RPG in which backstab can only be the first attack you do.<P>AND you have to be the attacking party (so you cannot backstab while being attacked or in a fight)<P>Backstab was also closely linked with "deathblow" which means instant death if Backstab has a 100% efficiency ...<P>Cybu<BR><I>The "what's that thing in your back" backstabber</I><p>[This message has been edited by Cybu (edited 17-10-2000).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Arhu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cybu: ~<I>if I'm not mistaking I know some (text based) RPG in which backstab can only be the first attack you do.</I>~<BR>And that is reasonable, considering the actual meaning of <I>back</I>stabbing. BG did this and even linked it to Hide in Shadows, which is also understandable, though it made a thief too powerful, and if not that, it at least led to save-reload-reload "gameplay". In the end, I used a thief to quickly dispatch almost anything in BG, while my fighters and mages stood around twiddling their thumbs, as Goe already described.<P>Sure it would be quite a story to hear about a legendary master thief (or ninja in this case) with unrivalled abilities, who could hide in shadows anytime and assassinated an entire army while no one has ever seen him, but it would be pretty boring if you could do such things, too. Someone here hinted that a thief's life is normally <I>not</I> easy, and it's just fine that way.<BR>Besides.. how would one backstab a knight who is clad in full plate armour? In open fights, a thief is normally lost, but his agility might prove to be useful at last. So, though the term "backstabbing" implies kind of a different meaning, a free attack is all right.<P>------------------<BR>Arhu<BR><I>"You will always be lucky if you know how to make friends with strange cats."</I> - Colonial American proverb</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</IFRAME>
</FONT>
